WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.880
[Amit Varma]: Iris Murdoch once said, quote, Love is the extremely difficult realisation that something

00:00:09.880 --> 00:00:14.260
[Amit Varma]: other than oneself is real, stop quote. I won't pontificate on love here, but I like

00:00:14.260 --> 00:00:18.360
[Amit Varma]: the phrasing of something other than oneself is real. If you've heard recent episodes

00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:22.920
[Amit Varma]: of the show, you might have heard me musing about our tendency to treat all other people

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:27.520
[Amit Varma]: like minor characters in a play or props in a scene in which we are the star and everyone

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:31.760
[Amit Varma]: else is there just to fulfil this function or that role. I think about this more and

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:36.800
[Amit Varma]: more these days, how reflexive it is to behave like the centre of the universe. And while

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:41.020
[Amit Varma]: this is something I grapple with at an individual level, where I try to be mindful of treating

00:00:41.020 --> 00:00:46.400
[Amit Varma]: people as well, actual people. This is also something that plays out between groups. And

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:51.200
[Amit Varma]: indeed, if you look at how men have treated women through the ages, you'll find that

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:57.120
[Amit Varma]: a lot of it is based on function. Women have been forced into different roles and stereotypes.

00:00:57.120 --> 00:01:02.360
[Amit Varma]: And anything outside of that has been treated as surplus to requirement. And at one level,

00:01:02.360 --> 00:01:06.120
[Amit Varma]: the roles women have been pushed into may seem to fall between the extremes of those

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:11.600
[Amit Varma]: cliches of the whore and the Madonna. A book called Intimate City written by my guest today

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:16.520
[Amit Varma]: shows that in some ways, those extremes are not opposites, but even the same thing. For

00:01:16.520 --> 00:01:21.520
[Amit Varma]: example, both sex workers and housewives are assumed to have given their consent away once

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:26.440
[Amit Varma]: they choose those roles. Marital rape is still not considered a crime in India. And lawyers

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:30.920
[Amit Varma]: have argued in court that the rape of a sex worker cannot be a big deal because well,

00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:35.840
[Amit Varma]: they're used to sex as sex workers. In a different context, my guest spoke about how at different

00:01:35.840 --> 00:01:41.320
[Amit Varma]: points in time, quote, life outside marriage or prostitution has been impossible for women.

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:45.120
[Amit Varma]: Stop good. You'll have to listen to this full conversation to hear the full argument. But

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:49.520
[Amit Varma]: for now, I'll share a third commonality between a sex worker and a housewife, as they have

00:01:49.520 --> 00:01:54.960
[Amit Varma]: typically existed, that they are both instrumental to the needs of the men in their lives, their

00:01:54.960 --> 00:01:59.920
[Amit Varma]: autonomy, their personal needs and desires. The interior lives don't matter. They fulfill

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:04.520
[Amit Varma]: a role. That's all that matters. And I think you'll agree with me that to reduce human

00:02:04.520 --> 00:02:14.040
[Amit Varma]: beings to this is a terrible crime. And we do it in many contexts other than this.

00:02:14.040 --> 00:02:19.240
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. Our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:28.240
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma. Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:33.200
[Amit Varma]: today is a sociologist Manjima Bhattacharya, author of a book called Intimate City, which

00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:37.960
[Amit Varma]: I loved and recommend to all of you. Intimate City is about the changing face of sex work

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:42.960
[Amit Varma]: across the world. And in India, it looks at how globalization and technology have transformed

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:47.120
[Amit Varma]: sex work. And I found many things here in common with the way the creator economy has

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:52.520
[Amit Varma]: evolved. The book also takes a close look at the way in which feminism has evolved in

00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:57.480
[Amit Varma]: how it looks at sex work. At first, appalled by the objectification and the presumed lack

00:02:57.480 --> 00:03:02.240
[Amit Varma]: of consent, but later accepting that all sex work does not arise out of trafficking. And

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:07.800
[Amit Varma]: sometimes women exercise their agency in choosing sex work over other available ways to make

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:12.360
[Amit Varma]: a living. At first, I thought this episode would be mainly about this book, and perhaps

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:16.160
[Amit Varma]: touch on Manjima's previous book, Manequin, which looked at the women who worked in India's

00:03:16.160 --> 00:03:20.320
[Amit Varma]: glamour industry. But as we got talking, I got more and more fascinated by Manjima's

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:25.560
[Amit Varma]: journey into feminism, activism, sociology, and just by the way her thinking evolved with

00:03:25.560 --> 00:03:30.080
[Amit Varma]: all the work and the writing she did. So the first half of this episode is about her journey

00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:34.120
[Amit Varma]: as a feminist. And then we talk about the changing face of sex work. There are many

00:03:34.120 --> 00:03:38.200
[Amit Varma]: sharp insights in this conversation. And while listening to the edit, I found myself forced

00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:42.360
[Amit Varma]: to stop and process some of them. I think you'll enjoy it as well. But before we get

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:48.800
